---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="The Map with No Names | River Roots Studio" description="Sometimes the most honest map is the one with no labels. An essay on following the river of intuition, and the seed of the Creative Compass.">
  <!-- PAGE HEADER -->
  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center">
      <h1 class="font-heading text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-moss leading-tight">
        The Map with No Names
      </h1>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ESSAY BODY -->
  <section class="pb-12 sm:pb-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 space-y-6 text-brown/80 text-lg leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Sometimes the most honest map is the one with no labels: just contours, rivers, and the faint trails left by those who wandered before us.
      </p>
      <p>
        I&rsquo;ve been thinking about this idea a lot lately. We spend so much of our lives trying to name things: our feelings, our purpose, our next step. And naming can be powerful: it can anchor us, give us language for what we&rsquo;re living through. But sometimes the naming comes too soon, before the thing has had a chance to simply <em>be</em>.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-semibold text-moss pt-4">What Happens When We Stop Naming</h2>
      <p>
        In our workshops, there&rsquo;s a moment that happens almost every time. Someone will be deep in their collage or their writing, and they&rsquo;ll pause. They&rsquo;ll look up and say something like, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what this means yet.&rdquo; And I always say the same thing: <em>Good. Let it not mean anything for a while.</em>
      </p>
      <p>
        That&rsquo;s the gift of expressive arts. It gives us permission to explore without explaining. To create without justifying. To follow a thread without knowing where it leads.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl font-semibold text-moss pt-4">Following the River</h2>
      <p>
        The name <em>River Roots</em> came from this same instinct. Rivers don&rsquo;t consult maps. They follow the path of least resistance, finding their way around stone and through soil. They don&rsquo;t rush. They just keep moving.
      </p>
      <p>
        What if we trusted ourselves to do the same?
      </p>

      <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-moss/30 pl-6 py-2 my-8">
        <p class="font-heading text-xl sm:text-2xl text-brown italic leading-relaxed">
          &ldquo;Not all those who wander are lost.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <footer class="text-brown/60 mt-2">
          <cite class="not-italic text-sm">&mdash; J.R.R. Tolkien</cite>
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        Next time you feel the urge to label what you&rsquo;re going through, try this instead: pick up a pen, a brush, a magazine. Let your hands do the thinking. You might be surprised by what your hands already know.
      </p>

      <!-- CONTEXT NOTE + RETURN LINK -->
      <div class="border-t border-moss/10 mt-10 pt-8 text-center">
        <p class="text-brown/60 text-base italic mb-3">This essay is the seed of the Creative Compass.</p>
        <a href="/creative-compass" class="text-moss hover:text-moss-dark font-medium transition-colors">
          &larr; Back to the Compass
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
